#Create functions to visualize the variables by Empirical Frequency (Bar chart for Categorical variables and Histogram for Continuous variables)
col <- "black"
fill <- "steelblue"
ylab <- "Relative Frequency"

ggplot.bar <- function(DT, variable, xlab, binwidth){
  ggplot(data = DT, aes(as.factor(variable))) + theme_bw() + 
    geom_bar(aes(y = (..count..)/sum(..count..)), binwidth=binwidth, col = col, fill = fill, alpha = 0.5) + labs(x = xlab, y = ylab)
}


ggplot.hist <- function(DT, variable, xlab, binwidth){
  ggplot(data = DT, aes(variable)) + theme_bw() + 
    geom_histogram(aes(y = (..count..)/sum(..count..)), binwidth = binwidth, col = col, fill = fill, alpha = 0.5) + 
    labs(x = xlab, y = ylab)
}

Grouping the variables

freq %>% 
  summarize(emp_freq = 
              sum(ClaimNb)/ sum(Exposure))
##     emp_freq
## 1 0.07057842
#DriverAge and CarAge and Density is grouped due to its large number of possible values, using Empirical frequency
#DriverAge by Empirical Frequency
driver_freq <- freq %>% 
  group_by (DriverAge) %>% 
    summarize(emp_freq = 
              sum(ClaimNb)/ sum(Exposure))
ggplot(driver_freq, aes(x=DriverAge, y=emp_freq))+
  geom_bar(stat="identity")

#Grouping DriverAge in Frequency dataset
freq <- freq %>%  
 mutate(driver_age_numbered = case_when(DriverAge>=0 & DriverAge<=20 ~ 0,
                                        DriverAge>21 & DriverAge<=26 ~ 1,
                                        DriverAge>=27 & DriverAge<=57 ~ 2,
                                        TRUE ~ 3))
#CarAge by Empirical Frequency
car_freq <- freq %>% 
  group_by (CarAge) %>% 
    summarize(emp_freq = 
              sum(ClaimNb)/ sum(Exposure))
ggplot(car_freq, aes(x=CarAge, y=emp_freq))+
  geom_bar(stat="identity")
